<|startoftext|>Headline:House speaker Ryan seeks to explain comments in last-minute speech
Content: "WASHINGTON (Reuters) - U.S. House Speaker Paul Ryan offered his view on the Trump administration’s policy on refugees on Thursday while he sought to clarify the remarks he made on a conference call with House GOP caucus leaders. Ryan spoke to more than 10 conference attendees, some of whom had demanded the speaker’s removal from the Republican National Convention because of his remarks, but he quickly conceded that the Trump administration is a national security risk . It is the third time after that on Tuesday in which Speaker Paul Ryan has issued a policy statement critical of recent arrivals from Iraq because of a number of the comments during a campaign speech. “The fact is that the terrorists have had to hide their guns, get married terrorists to marry them and are here to stay,” Ryan said after an earlier speech condemning the campaign for the Nov. 8 election. “People in this country have to come with good intentions. That is our principle. If you have any doubt about the right policies for the United States, put it to Congress and they can take action to implement them.” He declined to give his reasons for his comments, saying he had “not been fully vetted.” He was responding to Democrats’ complaints that Republican leaders have failed to stand by their pledge to admit refugees. “We have been here and we have done our job. No refugees’ admission is happening now,” Ryan said. Ryan was speaking after his colleague Mike DeBonis was taken off the stage by protesters for speaking to Republicans on the convention floor.     As the speakers finished their remarks and members of the convention began to leave, Ryan, a Republican who has been an outspoken advocate for the party in both houses of Congress, issued a statement: “At one time, our nation must know, and this time we must admit refugees.” ",<|endoftext|>
